items.title: How Synthflow AI is cutting through the noise in a loud AI voice category
items.author: Becca Szkutak
items.summary: - *Synthflow AI* is a Berlin-based no-code platform enabling enterprises to build HIPAA and GDPR compliant voice AI customer service agents with extensive integrations. - Since 2023, it has grown to 1,000 customers and processes 5 million calls monthly, showing *strong enterprise traction* and 90% retention. - After raising $20M Series A led by Accel, Synthflow plans to expand R&D and open a US office, aiming to lead in the *competitive conversational AI market*.

items.title: India’s GoKwik Raises $13M, Valued at $450M
items.author: Jagmeet Singh
items.summary: - *GoKwik*, an Indian e-commerce startup, raised a $13M growth round led by RTP Global, boosting its valuation to **$450M** pre-money, 43% higher than the previous valuation. - The startup supports over **12,000 merchants internationally**, facilitating D2C sales with integrated SaaS products and WhatsApp commerce solutions. - Plans include global expansion, AI enhancements, and enabling Indian merchants for international sales with a target to reach **profitability in 18 months** and IPO in 3–5 years.

items.title: Race to Build More Empathetic Language Models
items.summary:
- AI development is shifting focus from pure logic to *emotional intelligence* for deeper human-AI interactions.  
- Open-source tools like LAION's EmoNet and benchmarks such as EQ-Bench highlight advances in AI's ability to recognize and reason about emotions.  
- While emotionally savvy AI promises transformative benefits like mental health support, it also raises concerns about manipulation and emotional dependency on AI.

items.title: Facebook Group Admins Complain of Mass Bans; Meta Says It’s Fixing the Problem
items.summary: - Thousands of Facebook Groups worldwide faced *mass suspensions* due to a technical error. - Groups affected include large, innocuous communities wrongly flagged for *terrorism* or *nudity*. - Meta confirms awareness and is working on fixing the issue, suspected to stem from *faulty AI moderation*.

items.title: AI Medical Scribe Abridge Doubles Valuation to $5.3B in 4 Months
items.summary:
- *Abridge*, an AI startup automating medical notes, raised $300M Series E, doubling its valuation to **$5.3B** in just four months.
- The company leads the AI-powered medical scribe market, integrated with Epic Systems, and serves over **150** major US health systems.
- Expansion into AI-powered medical coding makes it directly competitive with other startups and Epic’s offerings.

items.title: The All-In Podcast’s $1,200 Tequila Sold Out Quickly
items.summary: - The popular All-In Podcast launched a *$1,200 tequila* in a limited run of *750 bottles*, packaged in poker-chip inspired containers. - The launch gala had a *1960s Rat Pack vibe* with notable tech and VC attendees. - The podcast hosts include influential VCs like Jason Calacanis, David Sacks, David Friedberg, and Chamath Palihapitiya.

items.title: iPhone Users Upset by Apple Wallet Ad for F1 Movie
items.author: Sarah Perez
items.summary: - Apple Wallet sent push notifications promoting the new Apple Original Film *F1 the Movie*, offering a $10 Fandango discount for ticket buyers.  - iPhone users express frustration over receiving unsolicited ads within their Wallet app, comparing it to past unpopular Apple marketing tactics.  - iOS 26 beta adds an option to disable Wallet offers, hinting at more future promotions, which many users oppose.

items.title: ElevenLabs Launches Standalone Voice Generation Mobile App
items.author: Ivan Mehta
items.summary:
- **ElevenLabs** released a native mobile app for iOS and Android that allows users to generate voice clips from text, previously available only via web app.
- The app offers about **10 minutes** of free audio generation with access to **v3 alpha text-to-speech models** featuring expression control.
- The company plans to add features like **speech-to-text**, conversational AI, and AI-powered experiences, targeting content creators and professionals.

items.title: Chrome for Android adds option to move address bar to bottom
items.summary:
- Google Chrome for Android now offers users the option to **move the address bar to the bottom** of the screen, enhancing one-handed usability.
- This feature mirrors a similar design Apple introduced in iOS 15 but is **optional and user-configurable** in Chrome, avoiding forced changes.
- The update will roll out gradually, allowing Android users to personalize their browsing experience according to preference.

items.title: Feds Question Ford in Hands-Free Driving Investigation
items.summary: - The NHTSA has sent Ford 25 detailed questions regarding its BlueCruise hands-free system after two fatal crashes. - The investigation focuses on BlueCruise's detection of stationary vehicles, especially under poor visibility conditions. - Ford must respond by August 6 or face penalties; the system costs $495/year or $2,495 one-time and is featured in several Ford models.

items.title: At TechCrunch Disrupt 2025, Experts Share How to Land a Winning Pitch
items.summary:
- *Medha Agarwal*, *Jyoti Bansal*, and *Jennifer Neundorfer* discuss key strategies to make startup pitches stand out at TechCrunch Disrupt 2025.
- The panel shares insights on building trust, highlighting subtle signals, and what investors look for to win funding.
- Join 10,000+ leaders at the event to explore high-impact discussions and save on tickets with early pricing.

items.title: Wispr Flow raises $30M from Menlo Ventures for AI dictation app
items.author: Ivan Mehta
items.summary:
- **Wispr Flow**, an AI-powered dictation app, raised $30M in Series A funding from Menlo Ventures and others, totaling $56M to date.
- The app supports **104 languages** and has grown its user base by 50% month-over-month, with significant use by non-technical users.
- Plans include Android launch, enterprise features, and evolving into a personal AI assistant for messaging, notes, and reminders.

items.title: Medha Agarwal, Jyoti Bansal & Jennifer Neundorfer on Pitch Success
items.summary: - *Industry leaders* Medha Agarwal, Jyoti Bansal, and Jennifer Neundorfer share insider tips on crafting standout pitches at TechCrunch Disrupt 2025. - They emphasize *trust-building, understanding subtle signals*, and *long-term founder support*. - Join 10,000+ tech and VC leaders October 27–29 in San Francisco for transformative startup insights.

items.title: Thanks to Fidelity and Sponsors, TechCrunch All Stage Empowers Startups
items.summary: - **TechCrunch All Stage** spotlights expert partners like Fidelity to deliver actionable insights for startups. - Sessions on **legal advice, fundraising, burnout, M&A readiness, and 2025 VC trends** provide must-attend guidance for founders. - Sponsors including Aktiun Inc, Brew, and UC Berkeley SCET fuel an energizing event on July 15 in Boston.

items.title: A federal judge sides with Anthropic in lawsuit over training AI on books without authors’ permission
Amazon to expand Prime delivery to rural US with $4B investment
items.summary: - Amazon is investing over **$4 billion** to expand its **Same-Day and Next-Day Prime delivery** to more than 4,000 rural towns in the US by 2026. - This will triple the size of its delivery network, create approximately 170 new jobs, and respond to growing rural demand for faster e-commerce delivery. - The announcement precedes the upcoming **Prime Day 2025** event, highlighting increased Prime service adoption with a 30% rise in fast deliveries year-over-year.

items.title: UK Considers Requiring Google to Offer Alternative Search Options
items.author: Ram Iyer
items.summary: - The UK Competition and Markets Authority (CMA) is considering designating Google with ‘strategic market status’ under new rules to enhance competition in search services. - This could force Google to provide alternative search options, enforce fairer ranking, and give publishers more control over content use in AI services. - The CMA will decide by October 13, aiming to increase *user choice* and stimulate *innovation* in the UK tech sector.

items.title: Google rolls out new Gemini model that can run on robots locally
How a data processing problem at Lyft became the basis for Eventual
Google adds historical Street View to Google Earth
items.summary:
- **Google Earth now features historical Street View imagery**, previously exclusive to Google Maps, expanding ways to explore places over time.
- This update celebrates **Google Earth’s 20th anniversary** and responds to a social media trend of virtual time traveling.
- New AI-powered insights like **tree canopy coverage and land surface temperature** are introduced for professional users, aiding urban planning in cities like Austin, Texas.

items.title: Novoloop is making tons of upcycled plastic
items.author: Tim De Chant
items.summary: - Novoloop has developed a process to *upcycle problematic waste plastics* (like single-use films) into valuable thermoplastic polyurethane (TPU), producing up to *70 metric tons per year* at its demo plant. - The company is *sold out* of its product and has secured $21M Series B funding to build a commercial-scale plant, planning to co-locate with existing chemical plants. - Their technology breaks down polyethylene into monomers and synthesizes higher-value polymers, with additional lines for recycling TPU scraps, advancing *circular plastic economy* goals.

items.title: US Bans WhatsApp on House of Representatives Staff Devices
items.summary: - The U.S. House of Representatives has banned WhatsApp on staff devices citing *high security risks* including lack of data transparency and encryption. - Alternative apps like *Signal, iMessage, FaceTime,* and *Microsoft Teams* are recommended instead. - Recent hacking campaigns linked to Israeli spyware maker *Paragon Solutions* have heightened concerns.

items.title: Uber and Waymo Launch Commercial Robotaxi Service in Atlanta
items.summary: - *Waymo robotaxis are now available via Uber in Atlanta, covering about 65 square miles.*  - The fleet starts with dozens of vehicles and will grow to hundreds shared with Austin.  - *Rides cost the same as equivalent human-driven Uber services, integrating autonomous and traditional vehicles through Uber's app.*

items.title: Google introduces AI mode to users in India
items.summary:
- Google launched its experimental *AI mode* for search in India, available via opt-in through Search Labs.
- The mode supports complex multi-part queries and follow-ups in English, with voice and image search features enabled.
- Powered by Gemini 2.5, this launch targets India's 870M+ internet users and aims to compete with chat-based AI tools like ChatGPT.

items.title: Court filings reveal OpenAI and io’s early work on an AI device
Tesla’s robotaxis have caught federal safety regulators' attention
items.summary: - *Tesla* began offering paid rides in its *robotaxis* in Austin, triggering scrutiny. - The U.S. *National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA)* contacted Tesla after videos showed potential *traffic violations* and unsafe behaviors. - Tesla robotaxis use an unsupervised Full Self-Driving system with a human safety monitor, but concerns about *speeding* and *wrong-lane driving* have emerged.

items.title: Databricks Co-founder Pledges $100M for New AI Research Fund
items.summary:
- Andy Konwinski, co-founder of Databricks and Perplexity, pledges $100M via his Laude company to launch the Laude Institute, supporting AI research with grants.
- The Institute’s flagship grant funds UC Berkeley’s AI Systems Lab, opening in 2027, led by Ion Stoica.
- The fund supports both early-stage “Slingshots” and ambitious “Moonshots” projects aiming for beneficial AI outcomes beyond commercial interests.

items.title: Apple’s Liquid Glass interface improves with release of iOS 26 Beta 2
Canada says telcos were breached in China-linked espionage hacks
Leak reveals Grok might soon edit your spreadsheets
Four months after a $3B valuation, Harvey AI grows to $5B
items.summary: - *Harvey AI* raised $300 million in Series E funding, doubling its valuation to **$5 billion** just four months after a $3 billion valuation round. - The startup, focused on *legal AI automation*, plans to double its workforce from 340 employees and expand into professional services like tax accounting. - Harvey serves 337 legal clients and has achieved an annualized revenue run-rate of **$75 million** as of April 2025.

items.title: TechCrunch Disrupt 2025: The Builders Stage agenda is now live and taking shape
Over a Million Users Now Access Gen-AI Powered Alexa+
items.summary:
- *Alexa+* by Amazon leverages *generative AI* to offer more natural, personalized digital assistant interactions and smart home control.
- Over a million users have gained early access; non-Prime users will pay $19.99/month post-launch, while Prime users get it free.
- Alexa+ supports natural language, personalized memory, and third-party integrations with key services like OpenTable and Ticketmaster.

items.title: New York State wants more nuclear power in a big way
AllSpice’s platform is the GitHub for electrical engineering teams
Senators urge FTC to investigate Spotify’s higher-priced bundled subscription
TikTok parent ByteDance is shutting down its short-lived book publisher
US insurance giant Aflac says customers’ personal data stolen during cyberattack
Where VCs Are Investing Next: TechCrunch Disrupt 2025 Preview
items.summary:
- *TechCrunch Disrupt 2025* gathers top VCs from Index Ventures, Greylock, and Felicis on Oct 27 to discuss 2026 investment trends in AI, data, cloud, and robotics.
- Founders will hear insights on automating overlooked industries, product-driven startups, and cloud/SaaS brand building from Nina Achadjian, Jerry Chen, and Viviana Faga.
- Early registration is open with significant ticket discounts for this key innovation and investment conference in San Francisco.

items.title: Japanese shipping firm NYK acquires Kadmos, a salary payment platform for seafarers
Google Adds AI Features to Chromebook Plus Devices
items.author: Ivan Mehta
items.summary:
- Google introduces **AI-powered tools** to Chromebook Plus devices, including a screen selection search tool, text simplification, and NotebookLM.
- New features leverage the **Quick Insert key** for AI image generation and writing assistance.
- Lenovo’s Chromebook Plus 14 gains exclusive AI for tab organization and image editing, bundled with a 1-year Google AI Pro subscription.

items.title: SMB-focused Finom closes €115M amid European fintech surge
items.summary: - Amsterdam-based challenger bank **Finom**, targeting European SMBs, secured a **€115M Series C round**, boosting total funding to about $346M. - Finom aims to reach *1 million business customers* by 2026, offering integrated banking, invoicing, and AI-enabled accounting. - The funding supports *growth, marketing, and strategic acquisitions*, with plans to expand lending and leverage AI internally.

items.title: OpenAI pulls promotional materials around Jony Ive deal
items.summary: - OpenAI removed a video promoting its $6.5B acquisition of Jony Ive’s startup io due to a **trademark lawsuit** over the 'io' name. - The deal and Ive’s role in leading design remain **on track**, not dissolved. - A judge issued a **restraining order** over the use of 'io,' prompting content removal to avoid consumer confusion.

items.title: Tesla Launches Robotaxi Rides in Austin Amid Questions
items.summary:
- Tesla has started offering *driverless Model Y robotaxi rides* in Austin, using only cameras and AI.
- Service initially small, about 10 vehicles, operating daily with a *human safety monitor* onboard.
- Significant *information gaps* and attempts to suppress public records; safety monitor role and ride specifics remain unclear.

items.title: Why Danny Boyle shot ‘28 Years Later’ on iPhones
items.summary:
- Director *Danny Boyle* used a rig of 20 iPhone Pro Max cameras to create a low-cost *bullet time* effect for brutal action scenes in *28 Years Later*.
- iPhones were the film’s *principal camera*, chosen for their mobility and ability to film in remote locations with minimal equipment.
- This approach contrasts with the original *28 Days Later*, shot on Canon digital cameras, highlighting Boyle's innovative use of *consumer tech* in filmmaking.

items.title: The stablecoin evangelist: Katie Haun’s fight for digital dollars
items.summary:
- *Katie Haun*, former federal prosecutor and crypto investor, champions stablecoins as crucial digital dollars stabilizing cryptocurrency volatility.
- Stablecoins have grown to a $250 billion market, facilitating cheap, global dollar transactions, especially valuable in unstable economies.
- Haun supports federal regulation (GENIUS Act) for clarity and safety but warns against outright bans on yield-bearing stablecoins, foreseeing tokenization transforming global assets.

items.title: Moratorium on state AI regulation clears Senate hurdle
items.summary:
- A Republican-backed rule would block states from enforcing AI regulations for 10 years by withholding federal broadband funding.
- Senate Parliamentarian ruled the provision can pass with a simple majority, bypassing a filibuster.
- The moratorium faces opposition from some Republicans and advocacy groups over concerns of state rights and regulatory gaps.

items.title: LinkedIn CEO: AI Writing Assistant Less Popular Than Expected
items.author: Anthony Ha
items.summary: - LinkedIn's AI writing assistant for polishing posts is *less popular* than CEO Ryan Roslansky anticipated, due to the high stakes of posting on a professional platform. - Users fear backlash from posts that appear *AI-generated*, impacting economic opportunities. - Meanwhile, demand for AI skills in jobs has *increased sixfold*, and user profiles reflecting AI skills have grown *twentyfold*. - Roslansky personally uses AI to refine emails, showcasing practical AI adoption.

items.title: Last day to save on your TechCrunch All Stage pass — prices go up tonight
items.summary:
- Today is the *final day* to secure discounted tickets for **TechCrunch All Stage 2025** on July 15 in Boston; prices increase at *11:59 p.m. PT.*  
- The event features *founders, investors, and operators* discussing fundraising, scaling, and leadership with speakers from Boldstart Ventures, Precursor Ventures, Sapphire Ventures, NEA, and more.  
- Attendees can expect *actionable sessions*, roundtables, pitch competitions, and side events, offering opportunities to connect and save up to *$210* by registering now.

items.title: European leaders worry they’re too reliant on U.S. tech
items.summary: - European governments are reconsidering reliance on American technology after Microsoft disabled the email of ICC's chief prosecutor due to U.S. sanctions. - This action highlighted fears that U.S. companies must comply with political pressures, prompting Europe to seek alternatives like Swiss email providers. - Microsoft has since adjusted policies and introduced 'sovereign solutions' to protect European institutions.
